  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Xuán
  author: Jo Yeom
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The clouds of Gogryeong followed you away,
    while the moon of Yeonsan shone upon me.
    Once I returned to my ancient home,
    gazing at the moon, I yearned for the golden palace.
    You ride again toward the imperial capital,
    watching the clouds, remembering your family.
    But clouds and moon are heartless things—
    who could know the sincerity of a subject's heart?
    At the parting of ways, we cannot bear to say goodbye,
    escorting you again and again west of the city walls.
    I only wish that you will go forward now,
    pass the examination, and let your good name flourish.
  footnotes:
    - The 'golden palace' (金闕) refers to the royal court, symbolizing official position and honor.
    - This poem celebrates the departure of a friend traveling to the capital for the civil service examination, a pivotal moment in a scholar's life in East Asian tradition.
